tweet: 5. Try to think of #suicide as part of life, like any other death. Suicide is preventable, though. But we've got to do more than PREVENT suicide; we've got to help the people around us build lives worth living. #SPSM

name: Dese'Rae L. Stage
tweet: Implore local mental and behavioral health professionals to get training in trauma-informed #suicide crisis techniques‚Äîand hold them accountable. Write to your representatives. Shout it from the rooftops. #SPSM

name: Dese'Rae L. Stage
tweet: Got time? Volunteer with one of the organizations I've already mentioned. Volunteer at a peer-based warmline if you have lived experience ( http://warmline.org¬†). #suicide #SPSM

tweet: Donate it to small, local non-profits that do good work, like Six Feet Over (@SuckItSuicide). Donate it to art-based advocacy projects, like good ol' Live Through This (@lttphoto). #SPSM #suicide

name: Dese'Rae L. Stage
tweet: 3. Know your resources. Save the number for the National #Suicide Prevention Lifeline (@800273TALK) in your phone. It's 1-800-273-8255. Save the number for Crisis Text Line (@crisistextline) in your phone. It's 741-741. #SPSM

name: Dese'Rae L. Stage
tweet: Learn about #suicide before it affects you personally, if you have that luxury. Learn everything you can. #SPSM

name: Dese'Rae L. Stage
tweet: 1. #Suicide is not just a problem of mental health. We have to see it as a result of life's troubles. @CDCgov reported in June that 54% of those who died by suicide between 1999-2016 DID NOT have a known mental health condition. #SPSM

name: Dese'Rae L. Stage
tweet: Something has to be done. The #suicide prevention field has proven itself useless (thus far). Despite our best efforts, the rates continue to rise. We have to change EVERYTHING. #SPSM

tweet: The #bullying narrative is reductive. #Suicide is complicated. And if we're going to talk about bullying, we need to paint the whole picture: EVERYONE exposed to bullying‚Äîthe bully, the bullied, and the witnesses‚Äîare at higher risk for suicide.
